Introduction¶

In this project, I evaluate two questions based on a set of movie data provided by TMDb:

  • How does revenue track with success metrics?
  • How does runtime change over time?
  • What are the general distributions and characteristics of movie budgets, revenue, and runtime?

For the scope of this project, I only aim to make general observations rather than employing rigorous statistical analysis. I also limit the scope of my analysis to data that is well-cleaned, without duplicates, and not missing values in order to assure validity. I do allow some missing values in the revenue, budgets, and runtim series due to personal interest of still exploring the data, but this is treated in a systematic way.

Issues with the Data¶

A few items are noticed at a glance from the .head() and .tail() functions above:

  • Some column values are separated by the pipe character. This may or may not be an issue.
  • Homepage has some NaN values. It's probably formatted in the wrong datatype. May need to be fixed.
  • The budget and revenue columns at the end sometimes appear in scientific notation. I might want to check the data type.
  • There's a date column, so I should probably check the data type for it.
  • Some of the budget_adj and revenue_adj values are 0.

A couple of things are noted from the above .info() property of the dataframe:

  • There are some columns that appear to be missing some data. These may or may not be an issue, but in the least, they will inhibit evaluations based on those columns. I'll list whether they are missing many or a few relative to the dataframe size also in case that is helpful later. We'll (abritrarily) here say that missing many means they have less than 10K rows.
    • imdb_id (missing just a few)
    • cast (missing just a few)
    • homepage (missing many)
    • director (missing just a few)
    • tagline (missing many)
    • keywords (missing many)
    • overview (missing just a few)
    • genres (missing just a few)
    • production_companies (missing many)
  • There are a few datatypes worth commenting on and potentially investigating. I'll do that in the next cell, but those columns are:
    • homepage (because of the NaN values noted earlier)
    • release_date (to make sure it is a date type)
    • Meanwhile, all the columns that look like they should be numbers are cast as such, so that's good.

Research Considerations¶

Missing Data Limitation

An initial limitation appears in the data due to missing values. Since the 'tagline', 'keywords', and 'production_companies' columns are missing quite a few values, it may not be fair to base my evaluations on these attributes. Some of the other columns are also missing values, though to a lesser degree. While many of these are likely irrelevant to quantitative analysis (such as the 'homepage' column), others like the 'cast' or 'diretor' could be fairly significant.

One option would be to simply drop any such row with missing values, but as movies can have significant variance in budget and revenue, this has a potential to skew our data. For instance, what if we dropped a movie that had one of the highest revenues ever simply because the cast values were missing? That's said, I'll focus on questions that are not encumbered by this limitation.

That said, a further limitation is that some of the 'budget_adj' and 'revenue_adj' values, while not technically missing, are listed as "0." Whereas, given the above logic, we might be inclinced to drop those columns, I personally am particularly interested in these values and will choose to proceed being careful with how I threat them.

Question 1: Does revenue track well with other metrics of success?

Interestingly, there are 3 columns that might could be used to evaluate how "successful" a movie was: 'revenue_adj' (used rather than 'revenue' to get the value adjusted for inflation), 'popularity', and 'vote_average'. I felt it would be interesting to see if these tracked at all with how much revenue a movie made.

Question 2: How has run-time changed over time?

I was curious if movies have gotten shorter or longer over time. Of course this is likely not a representative sample, but it's large enough to guess at possible trends (if they exist).

Question 3: What are the general distributions and characteristics of movie budgets, revenue, and runtime?

This question is purely a matter of curiosity. I'm interested in if most movies are short or long, cost a lot of money, and how much revenue they yield.

Data Cleaning¶

After reviewing the imported dataframe, it looks like the following actions should be taken:

  • Convert the 'release_date' column to a date datatype.
  • Remove the duplicate entry value.
  • Explore other possible duplicates in the'original_title' column to see if they need fixing (we'll be dropping 'imdb_id').
  • Drop irrelevant columns from the dataframe. Given the research considerations above, I can make the following reccomendations:
    • Aside from movie identifiers, I can drop all but the following columns for just looking at variables:
      • 'revenue_adj'
      • 'popularity'
      • 'vote_average'
      • 'release_year'
      • 'runtime'
      • 'budget_adj'
    • However, a couple of other columns may be of interst later as they relate to the variables being kept, so I'll leave them in just in case:
      • 'vote_count' (in case we find anything strange with 'vote_average')
      • 'release_date' (in case we find anything strange with 'vote_year')
    • And of course we do want to keep some identifiers. Since the 'imdb_id' was missing some data, let's keep:
      • 'id' (can be our index)
      • 'original_title' (for curiosity and descriptive purposes)
  • Resolve the problem of the 'revenue_adj' and 'budget_adj' 0 values
  • Does check that no other key numeric variables have problematic 0 values

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Question 1: Does revenue track well with other metrics of success?¶

We can get a quick sense of this with a scatter matrix.

In [45]:
success_metrics = ['revenue_adj', 'popularity', 'vote_average']
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df_clean.loc[:,success_metrics], figsize=(8,8));
plt.suptitle("Scatter Matrix of Adjusted Revenue, Popularity, & Vote Average Values");

This is actually pretty hard to tell due the number of extreme outliers here. However, given that we are interested in general trends, we can probably work at removing some of those outliers while still preserving the general meaning of the data.

Moreover, in looking at the histograms for 'revenue_adj' and 'popularity', we can see that the distributions were very narrow. We could then get rid of some of the outliers while barely changing the distribution at all. The histogram for 'vote_average' shows a more normal distribution, so it's harder to see where the obvious outliers are. We may be able to leave it the same.

Let's take a pretty basic approach of removing outliers that are 1.5 times the interquartile range on either side of the third quartile.

In [21]:
rev_IQF = 1.5 * (df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.75) - df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.25))
rev_outlier_high = df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.75) + rev_IQF
rev_outlier_low = df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.25) - rev_IQF
In [22]:
pop_IQF = 1.5 * (df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.75) - df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.25))
pop_outlier_high = df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.75) + pop_IQF
pop_outlier_low = df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.25) - pop_IQF

Now let's look at the data with the outliers removed:

In [48]:
df_success_sansoutliers = df_clean.query('popularity <= @pop_outlier_high & popularity >= @pop_outlier_low \
                                        & revenue_adj <= @rev_outlier_high & revenue_adj >= @rev_outlier_low')
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df_success_sansoutliers.loc[:,success_metrics], figsize=(8,8));
plt.suptitle("Scatter Matrix of Adjusted Revenue, Popularity, & Vote Average Values \n (Outliers Removed)");

The above is intersting as, in the original scattermatrix, we did as least seemingly notice a slight positive correlation between revenue and vote average, but that's almost gone here. Let's check what % of the data we got rid of when removing those outliers:

In [24]:
(len(df_clean.dropna()) - len(df_success_sansoutliers.dropna())) / len(df_clean.dropna()) * 100
Out[24]:
26.20653866113129

Almost 26%, that's a lot! This outlier method isn't working out so well. Out of curiosity, let's see what happens if we ran the same process with a much much stricter outlier definition. Arbitrarily, let's say they have to be 10 times (since so much of our data was in the "outlier" category earlier) the interquartile range away from either third quartile.

In [49]:
rev_IQF_10 = 10 * (df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.75) - df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.25))
rev_outlier_high_10 = df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.75) + rev_IQF_10
rev_outlier_low_10 = df_clean['revenue_adj'].quantile(0.25) - rev_IQF_10

pop_IQF_10 = 10 * (df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.75) - df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.25))
pop_outlier_high_10 = df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.75) + pop_IQF_10
pop_outlier_low_10 = df_clean['popularity'].quantile(0.25) - pop_IQF_10

df_success_sansoutliers_10 = df_clean.query('popularity <= @pop_outlier_high_10 & popularity >= @pop_outlier_low_10 \
                                        & revenue_adj <= @rev_outlier_high_10 & revenue_adj >= @rev_outlier_low_10')
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df_success_sansoutliers_10.loc[:,success_metrics], figsize=(8,8));
plt.suptitle("Scatter Matrix of Adjusted Revenue, Popularity, & Vote Average Values \n (Outliers Removed, Strict Definition)");
In [26]:
(len(df_clean.dropna()) - len(df_success_sansoutliers_10.dropna())) / len(df_clean.dropna()) * 100
Out[26]:
1.8681888946549041

This result is much more sensible as we recover the relationship between revenue an vote average and only removed ~2% of the data points. Depending on how rigorous we need to be, we could invoke other statistical tests to remove outliers such as utilizing standard deviations instead. But even from this level we can observe the general trend.

First, astoundingly, the movies that brought in the most revenue were not necessarily those with a higher popularity rating. While the highest revenue movie did have a high popularity score, many (with no clear trend) movies with have revenues could be found at all popularity scores. Moreover, a number of high popularity/low revenue movies exist. This is quite unexpected but could be explained if the popularity rating was created by some metric out of touch with actual movie attendance. For instance, if critics viewpoints weighed in more heavily or if a faulty polling metric was used. Overall, while most movies included in this dataset were of medium-to-low popularity AND revenue, there is no clear relationship between the two variables.

Second, there is a slight relationship between vote average and revenue in that revenue is positively (and exponentially) correlated with vote average up unto a score of about 8. After this value, the revenue drops drastically. This also is extremely interesting as it implies movies with the highest ratings on this metric don't actually make the most money. It's possible that such movies are rated as well-crafted movies but don't fall into categories like summer blockbusters that, while not necessarily as artistically excellent, draw in many viewers. Another explanation is that we simply don't have enough examples of >8 vote average to draw good conclusions about revenue (perhaps movies are almost never rated higher than 8).

Explanations for both strange patterns however are purely selective and further information about the success metrics given here, as well as more robust statistical metrics, would be needed to make better argumentation.

Conclusions¶

After cleaning the movie database and evaluating the relationships between variables in the "Exploratory Data Analysis" section above, we can make the following claims in relation to our proposed research questions:

  • Movies that are "popular" (as rated by the 'popularity' metric) do not predictably bring in much revenue.
    Many movies with high popularity values had low revenue values and vice verse, with no clear relationship between the variables. This suggests a possible fault in the way the popularity metric is compiled, polled, or otherwise. Alternative suggestions may also exist such as that the way a movie is perceived in value does not correlate with its actual attendance. Further information on how the popularity metric was obtained would be required to make an educated determination.
  • Movies that are have a high vote average sometimes bring in more revenue, but only to an extent.
    The relationship between a movie's revenue and vote average did seem to expoentially increase for a number of movies but only up to a voting average of about 8. This implies either errors in the data, a faulty metric, or some other interesting behavior of how higher rated movies might well not be those that are most attended. An alternative or compounding factor may be that, for whatever reason, we simply don't have much data on movies with vote counts higher than 8. Further information on the vote average metric would be needed to make an educated determination.
  • There is no apparent relationship between runtime and the year of a movie's release. Movies did not seem to get longer or shorter over time. That said, it did appears that the variance in run times might have increased towards 2010 and onwards, but a more rigorous statistical analysis would be required to make this claim.
  • A few interesting observations can be made when examining the adjusted budget, adjusted revenue, and runtime columns
    An exploration of this data through histograms and basic statistics allows for a few interesting claims to be made:
    • A more robust analysis of the data may require repair of the adjusted budget and revenue columns. These appear to have erroneously low data values where the numerical value given is really an expression of that number in "number of millions". For example, a value of "1" in the dataset may really refere to "1,000,000." This was found by comparing such minimums found in the data to the values found in wikipedia. Each of these low values would need to be checked against a trusted source to see if the values really are that low, or if they reflect that value in number of millions. This task is beyond the scope of this project however and does not impede us from making the observations made here due to the small number of such datapoints.
    • The preponderance of movies had budgets of less than 50,000,000 dollars with revenues less than 25,000,000 dollars. Distributions for both data series are very narrow.
    • The movie with the highest revenue in the dataset was Avatar. Comparing its revenue to its budget, it looks like its profits were likely exceedingly positive.
    • Nearly all runtime values were less than 200 minutes with the majority existing between 100 and 200 minutes. Analysis of the min and max runtimes shows that our dataset includes filmshorts (as short as ~2 minutes) and long documentaries (as long as 900 minutes).
